         <abstract>
            <p>The authors continue the investigation into the problem of finding the best approximation to the sum of a convergent series, $\sum^\infty_{n = 0}x^na_n$, where $\{a_n\}$ is a moment sequence. The case considered is where $x = 1$. This requires a proper subset of the set of all moment series. Instead of having $$a_n = \int^1_0 t^n d\phi(t)\quad\text{with}\quad \int^1_0 |d\phi(t)| = 1,$$ we have $$a_n = \int^1_0 t^n(1 - t)^\delta \psi(t)dt\quad\text{with}\quad \int^1_0|\psi(t)|^2 dt = 1.$$ With this subset, the authors find the best sequence-to-sequence transformation and show that the error in this transformation of $(n + 1)$ terms of the series is $$\frac{1}{2\delta\sqrt{2\delta - 1}} \frac{n + 1}{\binom{n + 2\delta}{n}} \sim \frac{\Gamma(2\delta])}{\sqrt{2\delta - 1}} \frac{1}{n^{2\delta - 1}}\quad\text{as}\quad n \rightarrow \infty.$$</p>
          </abstract>
